defaultWitness: 
defaultProfessor Robin Grimes,default Chief Scientific Adviser, Foreign and Commonwealth Office, gave evidence.
defaultQ1 default&#xa0; 
defaultChair:default Professor Grimes, welcome to this session. We periodically meet chief scientists with the various Departments on a 
defaultgetting
default-to-know-you basis. In fact, I was meeting last night with two of your colleagues—one from the Home Office and one from DEFRA—so there is quite a free-flowing dialogue between Parliament and the chief scientists, which we welcome. 
defaultBefore we get to the meat of the discussion, I want to ask you a question stemming from the exchange that I had with the Foreign Secretary on the Floor of the House yesterday. It is somewhat of a parochial matter, in that it affects my constituency and Stephen Mosley’s. I refer to the proposal that Veolia Environmental Services Ltd undertake the destruction of some chemical weapons stocks from 
defaultSyria
default. It is a very simple question: are you satisfied that the procedures that are in place are sufficiently robust for us to be able to say to our constituents that there is no additional risk to them, other than those presented by living around a chemical complex?
defaultProfessor Grimesdefault: The short answer to that is that I am entirely satisfied that the processes, protocols and safety issues are in place. The materials that we are going to be receiving in the 
defaultUK
default are the so-called B chemicals. In order to make an agent that is used in warfare, A chemicals are added to B chemicals, which actually make the agent. The first thing is that they have separated out those two components, and the B
default&#xa0;
defaultchemicals are the ones that we are taking. On their own, they are not in the range of chemical weapons materials.
defaultThe second thing is that those B chemicals are ones with which the 
defaultUK
default is used to dealing. We use them in a range of different chemical processes, including pharmaceuticals. We are also used to taking them, dealing with the left-over products and incinerating them, indeed at 
defaultEllesmere Port
default, so the health and safety issues and everything are in place.
defaultActually, can I say that I think it sends a very positive message that the 
defaultUK
default is in a position that we can routinely and easily deal with these sorts of materials? I think it is right and proper that we are accepting them and stepping up to the plate.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ2 default&#xa0; 
defaultStephen Mosley:default The site is in Andrew’s constituency, but it is within half a mile of my own constituency as well. If people who are concerned about the situation write to us asking for information that we do not know, are we able to forward them on to you and ask for a response from the Foreign Office?
defaultProfessor Grimesdefault: I think that would be right, yes; I don’t see why not. I am only 10
default&#xa0;
defaultmonths into the job. I have not had that one before, but yes, I think that would be perfectly okay.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ3 default&#xa0; 
defaultChair:default Thanks very much. Moving on to more general issues, in your short time what do you see as the most pressing scientific issue facing the FCO?
defaultProfessor Grimesdefault: Gosh! There are lots of different issues, certainly around climate change, in trying to get our agenda forward internationally, which I think is important. In generic terms, having science increasing up the agenda, and the Foreign Office pushing that agenda, is very important. I am passionately keen that we are able to really use our strengths academically, industrially and in terms of our national labs, to further our national position. It is a rather broad thing, I’m afraid.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ4 default&#xa0; 
defaultChair:default I understand that the Department has found some money to expand your office. Are all the positions now filled?
defaultProfessor Grimesdefault: They will be filled by the middle of February. We have Andrew sitting here, who is my deputy, so today you are seeing some of those new positions filled. Of course, they are reassignments of existing positions within the FCO.
default&#xa0;
defaultQ5 default&#xa0; 
defaultChair:default But does this mean you will be able to take on more work in the Department than was traditionally the case?
defaultProfessor Grimesdefault: Yes. We have already been doing that. The Foreign Office is very open and welcoming to more work in science, technology, engineering and medical-related matters as well. We have to prioritise obviously, but it is looking great.
